05085nam a22006375i 9780823296811DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20211994nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232968117 a10.1515/97808232968112doi  a(DE-B1597)575221  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0040202bisacsh1 aBelitt, Ben, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Forgèd Feature :bTowards a Poetics of Uncertainty, New and Selected Essays /cBen Belitt. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2021] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (279 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tForeword -- tI. The Forged Feature: Pursuits and Predicaments -- tA. Pursuits -- t1. Literature and Belief: Three "Spiritual Exercises" -- t2. Meaning and the Sonal Imagination -- t3. In Search of the American Scene: "Demographic Vistas" -- tB. Predicaments -- t4. The Enigmatic Predicament: Some Parables of Kafka and Borges -- t5. The Heraldry of Accommodation: A House for Mr. Naipaul -- t6. The Depth Factor: Saul Bellow -- t7. Memoir as Myth: The Odysseys of Pablo Neruda -- tC. Translation: Grammars and Consciences -- t8. The Translator as Nobody in Particular: Faiths and Fidelities -- t9. Lowell's Imitations: Translation as Personal Mode -- t10. The Vanishing Original: Transvaluations -- tII. Toward a Poetics of Uncertainty: Trial Balances -- tPreface -- t11. Toward a Poetics of Uncertainty -- t12. Sight: Second or Sudden-Versions of Witness -- t13. Hopkins Observing: "Rehearsals" -- t14. Hopkins Transforming: "It Changed Beautiful Changes"0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe scope of The Forged Feature is two-fold: to bring together a representative selection of critical essays bearing on Belitt's interests as poet, critic, teacher, and translator; and to furnish an on-going review of his concern with the encoding of languages and the exigencies of their imaginative retrieval. The collection begins with three pieces on the uses of belief, linguistic and place as shaping forces in the concretizing of the literary artifact. The second section of essays examines the fictive medium in terms of a number of "predicaments." The discussion embraces texts such as parables, novels, and autobiographical meoirs covering a broad range of twentieth century talents: Kafka, Borges, V.S. Naipaul, Saul Bellows, and Pablo Neruda. The third section is devoted to the theory and practice of translation developed from Belitt's personal lifetime of experience. Finally, there is a sequence of four essays on the uses of "new physics" of quantum mechanics and its uncanny relevance to the accountability of poetry. Belitt re-evaluates Gerard Manley Hopkins as a "scientific" rather than a priestly crafter of a medium, and touches upon diverse traditions and talents such as Keats, Blake, Stevens, Bishop, Yeats, Baudelaire, Rimbaud, Cocteau, W.C. Williams, Michado, Rilke, Wordsworth, and Coleridge. The brilliant observations collected in this volume are not contained within a specific school of thought and are indefinable within any current fashion- rather, Belitt's frame of reference is literature itself and his essays proceed in a literary, poetic, and individual voice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311118960408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z97831107432960 cprintz978082321604840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329681140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978082329681142